package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: allocator-api2
  version: 0.2.21
  revision: 63cd7fcc2f8854b5821c7054d026e8a4647acde1
  digest: DwR6VgEd9XHm8RRoBZP01L6LJC0TRcxIRisy43fvdIw
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: medium
  rating: neutral
issues:
- id: missing-safety-comments-in-boxed-and-raw_vec
  severity: medium
  comment: |
    Many `unsafe { ... }` blocks lack the `// SAFETY:` justification
    that the upstream rust-lang/rust copy carries. Concrete examples
    in src/stable/boxed.rs: lines 368 (Box::new_in's write+
    assume_init), 395 (try_new_in equivalent), 472
    (try_new_uninit_in's Box::from_raw_in), 545 (try_new_zeroed_in
    equivalent), 571 (Box<[T;1]> cast). 75 unsafe blocks but only
    1 SAFETY comment in that file. src/stable/raw_vec.rs has 8
    unsafe blocks and zero SAFETY comments (lines 243, 279, 299,
    338, 471, 543, 579). Caps rating at neutral per rubric §2.
- id: no-ci-config-in-tarball
  severity: low
  comment: |
    Published tarball contains no .github/ or CI config files (the
    `exclude` field in Cargo.toml.orig isn't visible in the
    normalized Cargo.toml, but the effect is the same). Cannot
    verify whether upstream CI runs miri without leaving the source
    snapshot. Treating as "no observable miri" per rubric §3; caps
    independently at positive but dominated by §2.
comment: |-
  This crate mirrors Rust's unstable `allocator_api` for use on
  stable. The README states upfront that "the code is mostly verbatim
  copy from rust repository. Mostly attributes are removed." It is
  depended on by hashbrown (when not using std) and a number of
  alternative allocator/collection crates.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious/suspicious): `build = false` (no build.rs),
  no proc-macro, no `include_bytes!`, no Command/syscalls, no
  network. Dependencies: only optional `serde`. Features cleanly
  partition std/alloc/no_alloc and nightly (which re-exports
  core/alloc directly via src/nightly.rs). License MIT OR
  Apache-2.0. Author zakarumych is the maintainer of rendy and a
  long-time gfx-rs contributor; repository link valid.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): 277 `unsafe` occurrences across 12
  files, 54 `// SAFETY:` comments. Coverage is uneven:
  - src/stable/alloc/mod.rs (the Allocator trait): well-commented.
    Every unsafe block has a preceding SAFETY: comment.
  - src/stable/boxed.rs (2272 lines, 75 unsafe blocks): only 1
    SAFETY: comment. Stripped from the std original.
  - src/stable/raw_vec.rs (642 lines, 8 unsafe blocks): zero
    SAFETY: comments.
  - src/stable/vec/mod.rs (3232 lines, 56 unsafe blocks): 17
    SAFETY: comments — partial.
  Because this is allocation-adjacent code (raw_vec, Box, Vec), the
  missing SAFETY annotations are particularly worth flagging: this
  is exactly where bad assumptions become use-after-free or
  uninitialised reads. Per rubric §2 this caps the rating at
  neutral.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): No CI config in the published tarball; cannot
  verify miri usage from source alone. The unsafe here is almost
  entirely pure-Rust pointer manipulation (raw pointers,
  MaybeUninit, NonNull, ptr::copy_nonoverlapping) — exactly the
  flavour miri excels at. Treating as no observable miri; caps at
  positive, dominated by §2.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): The crate is structurally a port of
  alloc's Box/Vec/RawVec/etc, which has been extensively audited
  upstream. Spot-checked the Allocator trait's default grow/shrink
  implementations (alloc/mod.rs:196-285) and the size_of==0 ZST
  branch in Box::try_new_uninit_in (boxed.rs:465-472) — both match
  the upstream pattern. Did NOT attempt to walk all 8028 lines for
  drift; that would require a side-by-side with a specific std
  revision. Thoroughness medium accordingly.
  
  Did NOT run any code (no cargo build/test/expand) per project
  rules.
